WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.280
Yeah, thank you everyone, and welcome to the Strange Downloads Lighting Talk, where

00:00:12.280 --> 00:00:16.340
you're going to learn how to use the pins package to make sure your data science workflow

00:00:16.340 --> 00:00:18.240
remains reproducible.

00:00:18.240 --> 00:00:21.480
Now I know that most of you take reproducibility for granted.

00:00:21.480 --> 00:00:25.280
You think or you want to live in a world where everything is reproducible, and you know,

00:00:25.280 --> 00:00:28.600
to be fair, we have like great tools like rmarkdown, which was designed from the very

00:00:28.600 --> 00:00:30.680
beginning to be reproducible.

00:00:30.680 --> 00:00:35.000
However, you know, you want to be able to copy paste stuff anywhere, right?

00:00:35.000 --> 00:00:39.799
You want to be able to grab R code and place it on a different R session.

00:00:39.799 --> 00:00:43.540
You want to be able to grab that same code and put it on a different machine, and that

00:00:43.540 --> 00:00:45.560
all should work really nicely.

00:00:45.560 --> 00:00:46.560
And that's the case.

00:00:46.560 --> 00:00:48.599
And if that's the world where you live, you're very lucky.

00:00:48.599 --> 00:00:52.520
Well, let me tell you now about a very, very dark place, which I happen to call the upside

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:54.480
down of data science.

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:59.160
So in this world, not everything is as reproducible as it may seem, and you might find that there's

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:02.180
code that requires very strange downloads.

00:01:02.180 --> 00:01:06.559
So for instance, in this case, we have a package that supports Python and R, and when you copy

00:01:06.559 --> 00:01:09.000
paste the code, it basically doesn't work, right?

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:14.000
It's going to fail, because one thing that you find over and over is that there's like

00:01:14.000 --> 00:01:18.800
a local file named whatever.csv, and when you run the code, it doesn't exist.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:22.800
So you need to scroll all the way up and figure out, like, how exactly to download the file,

00:01:22.800 --> 00:01:25.919
then you download it, then you put it on a specific path, you change the code to point

00:01:25.919 --> 00:01:29.160
to that path, and when you want to rerun the code in a different session or a different

00:01:29.160 --> 00:01:31.320
machine, you do it all over again.

00:01:31.320 --> 00:01:33.239
So is there a better way to do this?

00:01:33.239 --> 00:01:38.400
Well, today we're going to find a way of closing this awful portal to the upside down of data

00:01:38.400 --> 00:01:46.440
science with a new pins package, which basically, all it does, it allows you to download a remote

00:01:46.440 --> 00:01:48.540
resource locally.

00:01:48.540 --> 00:01:53.339
So all you have to do is say pin, and then you have a URL, and it basically converts

00:01:53.339 --> 00:01:58.220
the remote URL into a local URL, and that's about it.

00:01:58.220 --> 00:02:01.739
Then you can make use of that resource, and not only that, but the pins package allows

00:02:01.739 --> 00:02:06.220
you to cache the resource, so if you rerun the code, we're not going to be redownloading

00:02:06.220 --> 00:02:10.100
this over and over again, and if you happen to lose internet connection and you run this

00:02:10.100 --> 00:02:15.259
code, the package isn't smart enough to not rerun the code and just use the cached version

00:02:15.259 --> 00:02:17.300
and make sure your code doesn't break.

00:02:17.300 --> 00:02:18.300
But what else?

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:23.139
I'm sure a lot of you work with data sets, and sometimes you tidy your data set, and

00:02:23.139 --> 00:02:27.059
then you wish you could share that with others, and the pins package also allows you to do

00:02:27.059 --> 00:02:28.059
that.

00:02:28.059 --> 00:02:33.059
You can say pin with a specific board, and then all you have to do is register your board,

00:02:33.059 --> 00:02:38.699
so for instance, you have boards for Kaggle, GitHub, RStudio Connect, Azure, Google Cloud,

00:02:38.699 --> 00:02:44.539
and S3, and whenever you pin a remote local data set, you basically are sharing it in

00:02:44.539 --> 00:02:48.220
these remote cloud providers or products.

00:02:48.220 --> 00:02:51.539
That's about it, and let's see if I can get a little demo to work.

00:02:51.539 --> 00:02:52.539
No, it won't work, so thank you.

00:02:52.539 --> 00:02:53.539
That's it.

00:02:53.539 --> 00:02:53.539


